Project Stage - III (Distributions and Hypothesis Testing)¶

Goals¶

The goal of Stage III is to develop distributions and formal hypothesis tests for the intuitions you had in Stage I and II and utilize statistical modeling to prove/disprove them.

Notice that it is individual work this time!

Task: (100 pts)¶

  • Member:

    • Use the state data (the state of your choice) generated in Stage II to fit a distribution to the number of COVID-19 cases. (25 points)
      • Graphically plot the distribution and describe the distribution statistics. If using discrete values, calculate the Probability Mass Function for the individual values or range (if using histogram) and plot that.
      • Describe the type of distribution (modality) and its statistics (moments of a distribution - center, variance, skewness, kurtosis) in the report and the notebook.
      • Compare the distribution and its statistics to 5 other states of your choosing. Describe if the distributions look different and what does that imply.

    • Model a poission distribution of COVID-19 cases and deaths of a state and compare to other 5 states. Describe how the poission modeling is different from the first modeling you did. (25 points)

      • For example, number of new cases and deaths per 100,000 population.
      • Hint - the parameter for a poission's distribution will be its mean value. Then for the minimum and maximum range of covid cases you are calculating probability mass function to observe the probability at different points.

    • Perform corelation between Enrichment data valiables and COVID-19 cases to observe any patterns. (20 points)

      • You can compare either within your chosen specific state or among different states with the different enrichment variables. Within the state you can compare the county based covid data to enrichment data for correlation. Between states you would need to aggregate to state level data and then perform correlation. Both covid and enrichment data will need to be normalized for population. For number of covid cases you can use a measure of center value (median or mean) to compare the number of cases.
    • Formulate hypothesis between Enrichment data and number of cases to be compared against states. Choose 3 different variables to compare against. (30 points)
      • For example: Does higher employment data lead to higher covid case numbers or more rapid increase in covid cases.

def get_dates(data):
    dates = data.loc[:, [i not in ["countyFIPS","County Name", "State", "StateFIPS"] for i in data]] #Extract non dates
    
    dates.columns = pd.to_datetime(dates.columns) #Fix columns to be date times
    
    dates = dates.loc[:, [(i <= datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 27)) and (i >= datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 6)) for i in dates]] #Extract correct time
    return dates

def get_weekly_stats(dates): #Note: was written for deaths, but should work the same for infect

    weeks = [range(i, i + 7) for i in range(0, len(dates.columns), 7)]
    dates.iloc[:, weeks[0]]
    
    stats = pd.DataFrame({"week": [],"mean" : [], "median" : [], "mode" : []})
    
    for i in range(len(weeks)):
        date = dates.iloc[:, weeks[i]].iloc[0, :].keys()[0]
        #print(date)
        week = dates.iloc[:, weeks[i]].sum(axis = 1)
        #print(week)
        #print(week.mean())
        #print(week.median())
        #print(week.mode())
        #print(death_stats)
        new_row = pd.DataFrame({"week": date,"mean" : week.mean(), "median" : week.median(), "mode" : week.mode()})
        stats = pd.concat([stats, new_row])
    return stats

def get_state_dates(data, state : str):
    '''Filter out all data not from a given state from data'''
    data = data[data["State"] == state]
    dates = data.loc[:, [i not in ["countyFIPS","County Name", "State", "StateFIPS"] for i in data]] #Extract non dates
    
    dates.columns = pd.to_datetime(dates.columns) #Fix columns to be date times
    
    dates = dates.loc[:, [(i <= datetime.datetime(2020, 12, 27)) and (i >= datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 6)) for i in dates]] #Extract correct time
    return dates

def get_stats(dates, normalize = True):
    date_sum = dates.sum()
    
    max_val = max(date_sum)
    min_val = min(date_sum)
    mode = stats.mode(date_sum, keepdims = False)
    mean = date_sum.mean()
    median = date_sum.median()
    
    variance = date_sum.var()
    
    skewness = stats.skew(date_sum)
    kurtosis = stats.kurtosis(date_sum)
    
    stv = date_sum.std()
    
    return mean, median, mode, variance, skewness, kurtosis, max_val, min_val, stv

for i in [(fl_cases, "fl_cases")]:
    mean, median, mode, variance, skewness, kurtosis, max_val, min_val, stv = get_stats(i[0])
    name = i[1]
    alpha = (mean ** 2)/(variance)
    beta = (variance)/mean
    print(f'''For {name},
    Mesures of center: mean = {mean}, median = {median}, mode = {mode}
    
    other stats: variance = {variance}, skewness = {skewness} (Note: Higher number = more right skewed, lower number = more left skewed, 0 = not skewed)
    kurtosis = {kurtosis}
    
    __________________________________________''')
    #plt.figure(figsize = (8,6))

    #Used chatGPT to tell me to use linspace.
    
    x_range = np.linspace(min_val, max_val, 300)
    
    #Histogram
    plt.figure(figsize = (8,6))
    
    plt.title('Histogram and Gamma Distribution for %s'%name)
    plt.hist(i[0].sum(), bins = 30, density = True, label = "Histogram %s"%name)
    
    
    
    #Gamma distrabution
    plt.plot(x_range, stats.distributions.gamma.pdf(x_range, alpha, scale = beta), label="Gamma %s"%name) #NoteL Multiplied by mean * 10 to make them fit, this should not affect the shape of the distrabution.
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

def get_state_spread(state):

    state_sum = state_cases.sum()

def make_poission(state, dataset):
    dates = get_state_dates(dataset, state)
    population = combined[combined["State"] == state]["population"].sum()
    dates /= population
    dates *= 100000
    date_sum = dates.sum()
    
    
    
    #Normalise for population
    
    mean, median, mode, variance, skewness, kurtosis, max_val, min_val, stv = get_stats(dates)
    #got how to make poisson distrabution from https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.stats.poisson.html
    
    #Break into bins and work off of those.
    
    #Splitting into 30 bins
    bin_num = 30
    
    step = (max_val - min_val)/bin_num
    
    bins = [[0]] * bin_num
    
    def get_bin(num):
        return (num - min_val) // step
    
    bin_map = date_sum.map(get_bin)
    #print(bin_map)
    mu = bin_map.mean()
    
    #Used chatGPT to tell me to use linspace.
    
    x_range = np.linspace(0, 30, 30)
    
    #Histogram
    plt.figure(figsize = (8,6))
    #plt.hist(date_sum, bins = 30, density = True, label = "Histogram %s"%name)
    plt.title('Poission Distribution for %s'%state)
    #Poission distrabutuin
    plt.plot(bin_map, stats.poisson.pmf(bin_map, mu))
    plt.hist(bin_map, density = True, bins = bin_num)
